</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usuzannadreamingheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SuzannaDreamingheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#333333>(7/4/02 11:57:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1361.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ArchMage Spec: Evoke Sirocco vs. Spec: Conj SoFB</span><hr size=1> Ok, I have done the analysis, and boy was it tedious. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Spell Description:<br>
============<br>
<br>
Sirocco has 3 waves which can each land for a maximum of 630 damage. Each wave can land for full, be fully resisted, or land for a partial. It was observed that in all cases (with no exceptions) that when a partial was achieved, it was an exact multiple of 63 damage, ie, in tenths of the full damage.<br>
<br>
Representation of the data:<br>
====================<br>
<br>
Each cast of the spell, the results are represented in the table below as the total damage caused by that spell, the sum of the 3 waves. However, it is shown not as hitpoints of damage, but instead, as units of 63 hitpoints each. This means, that a Sirocco spell hitting for full damage will land for a total of 30 units, 10 units of 63 damage each on each of the 3 waves. It is presented in this way, as the damage is always an exact multiple of 63.<br>
<br>
The Test Conditions:<br>
===============<br>
<br>
This test was carried out over 8 days, with some of those days split over 2 or 3 sessions. The data is summed over all sessions.<br>
<br>
Sirocco cast a total of 386 times.<br>
<br>
The Raw Data:<br>
==========<br>
<br>
The first number is the number of units of 63 hitpoints that a single cast of Sirocco can do. The second number is the number of occasions upon which that amount of damage was recorded. So, for example, on 150 occasions, Sirocco landed for 30 units of damage (ie, full damage on all three waves).<br>
<br>
30 - 150<br>
29 - 4<br>
28 - 1<br>
27 - 3<br>
26 - 3<br>
25 - 3<br>
24 - 7<br>
23 - 2<br>
22 - 4<br>
21 - 2<br>
20 - 129<br>
19 - 2<br>
18 - 6<br>
16 - 4<br>
14 - 7<br>
13 - 2<br>
12 - 6<br>
11 - 1<br>
10 - 42<br>
8  - 1<br>
7  - 1<br>
5  - 1<br>
2  - 1<br>
0  - 4<br>
<br>
Data Summary:<br>
==========<br>
<br>
Total Damage Inflicted: 8661 units<br>
Total Number of Casts: 386<br>
<br>
Therefore:<br>
<br>
Average Damage per Cast = 22.44 units.<br>
Average number of waves hitting = 2.24<br>
<br>
In hitpoints, this equates to an average damage of 1414 hitpoints.<br>
<br>
With a Specialization of 200 in Evocation, and a raw mana cost of 399 (let's call that 400), the effective mana cost is 320 (ignoring AA skills, etc). This gives the excellent DPM rating of 4.42.<br>
<br>
This compares *very* favourably with the 'perfect' DPM for SOFB of 4.14, which in practice will be somewhat less due to resists, I would estimate in the region of 3.8 (Feel free to conduct a study into this, my 3.8 figure is a finger in the air only).<br>
<br>
Notes:<br>
=====<br>
<br>
1) All hunting was done in Akheva. Hunting done elsewhere was removed from the log before analysis.<br>
2) All hunting was done solo. Hunting done in groups was removed from the log before analysis.<br>
3) This was normal xp hunting, just with logging switched on.<br>
4) All the mobs were either Centi Dators or Transient Patrollers, pops in the front area of the zone.<br>
5) Each mob was pulled with Malosini, as per my usual hunting style.<br>
6) Sirocco was never used to try to get the final blow. I have observed (like others) that resist rates go right up for this case. Instead, mobs were generally finished off with either Char, Sigil or Seukors, or by the pet.<br>
7) Most mobs had 2 siroccos cast on them. A few had 3, and a very few had only 1.<br>
8 )  During the period of the test, Suzanna gained Fury 1 AA skill. There were about 5 occasions where she achieved a 'crit' as a result. The 'crit' portion was simply removed as part of the analysis. For example, in 4 of these 5 cases, a wave landed for 840 instead of for 630, and so it was assumed to have done '630' non-crit damage for the purpose of this analysis (i.e. the effect of the crit was removed).<br>
9) On only 2 of the 386 casts, sirocco hit another target. The hits on the other target in both cases were removed from the analysis.<br>
<br>
Conclusion:<br>
=======<br>
<br>
I had contended I could output considerable damage with Sirocco. Estimates were made at the start of this thread that if 2 of the 3 waves landed on average, Sirocco would be more efficient than SOFB. This test suggests, that Sirocco infact is even better than estimated there.<br>
<br>
I am *more* than happy that for a seldom-raiding mage, Evocation is an excellent choice, even for an Archmage, and this data only serves to re-inforce my original statement, that if all other things are equal (gear / AA skills), an evocation mage *will* outdamage a conjuration mage over time, using Sirocco, under the right circumstances.<br>
<br>
/bow.<br>
